SIMPLE: fold
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fold
<hw>Fold</hw> <pr>(f⟦omac⟧ld)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Folded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Folding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>folden</ets>,
<ets>falden</ets>, AS. <ets>fealdan</ets>; akin to OHG.
<ets>faltan</ets>, <ets>faldan</ets>, G. <ets>falten</ets>, Icel.
<ets>falda</ets>, Dan. <ets>folde</ets>, Sw. <ets>f⟦aring⟧lla</ets>,
Goth. <ets>fal⟦thorn⟧an</ets>, cf. Gr. <grk>di-pla`sios</grk> twofold,
Skr. <ets>pu⟦tsdot⟧a</ets> a fold. Cf. <er>Fauteuil</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To lap or lay in plaits or folds; to lay one part over
another part of; to double; <as>as, to <ex>fold</ex> cloth; to
<ex>fold</ex> a letter.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As a vesture shalt thou <qex>fold</qex> them up.</q> <rj><qau>Heb.
i. 12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To double or lay together, as the arms or the hands;
<as>as, he <ex>folds</ex> his arms in despair</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To inclose within folds or plaitings; to envelop; to
infold; to clasp; to embrace.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A face <qex>folded in sorrow</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>J.
Webster.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We will descend and <qex>fold</qex> him in our arms.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To cover or wrap up; to conceal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor <qex>fold</qex> my fault in cleanly coined excuses.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fold</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fold
<hw>Fold</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become folded, plaited, or
doubled; to close over another of the same kind; to double together;
<as>as, the leaves of the door <ex>fold</ex></as>.</def> <rj><au>1 Kings
vi. 34.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fold</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fold
<hw>Fold</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Fold</er>, <pos>v.</pos> In
sense 2 AS. <ets>-feald</ets>, akin to <ets>fealdan</ets> to
fold.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A doubling,esp. of any flexible substance;
a part laid over on another part; a plait; a plication.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mummies . . . shrouded in a number of <qex>folds</qex> of
linen.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> <qex>Folds</qex> are most common in the rocks of mountainous
regions.</q> <rj><qau>J. D. Dana.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Times or repetitions; -- used with numerals, chiefly
in composition, to denote multiplication or increase in a geometrical
ratio, the doubling, tripling, etc., of anything; <as>as,
four<ex>fold</ex>, four times, increased in a quadruple ratio,
multiplied by four</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is folded together, or which infolds or
envelops; embrace.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Shall from your neck unloose his amorous <qex>fold</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fold net</b></col>, <cd>a kind of net used in catching
birds.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fold</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Fold
<hw>Fold</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>fald</ets>, <ets>fold</ets>,
AS. <ets>fald</ets>, <ets>falod</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An
inclosure for sheep; a sheep pen.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Leaps o'er the fence with ease into the <qex>fold</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A flock of sheep; figuratively, the Church or a
church; <as>as, Christ's <ex>fold</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> There shall be one <qex>fold</qex> and one shepherd.</q>
<rj><qau>John x. 16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> The very whitest lamb in all my <qex>fold</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A boundary; a limit.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Creech.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fold yard</b></col>, <cd>an inclosure for sheep or
cattle.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fold</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Fold
<hw>Fold</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To confine in a fold, as
sheep.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fold</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Fold
<hw>Fold</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To confine sheep in a fold.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The star that bids the shepherd <qex>fold</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

